Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another row of excellent results in exams, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further higher education, for their chosen career and country as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored education curriculum, we are witnessing how the branch of modern languages continues to be a widespread and popular choice across schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language he understands, your words go to his ears.
If you speak to him in his own language, your words go to his heart.
These words are a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of this year's final exams, we can find that languages are toping the list of results, with the highest rate of passing grades between private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages have received the maximum grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIs member schools showed that 72 per cent of students received the maximum grade A in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those studying for German, 69 per cent of those studying for French and 63 per cent of those studying for Spanish had also received the grade A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, the branch of foreign languages is considered as important as STEM branches (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in private school curricula and beyond.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the main difficulties employers faced for filling vacancies, 17 percent of them were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for preparing young people for their future careers.
With the addition of jobs that have as a condition the possession of foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of a person's career, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as the owner of such a long-term skill.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign people will automatically position a multilingual person over competitors.
According to a YouGov poll, which included over 4000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only foreign language spoken by a percentage of people with 2 digits, namely 15 percent.
That's why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
Owning many languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in them.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a range of languages you can choose from in private schools, with pedagogical staff consisting of field specialists.
Private Scottish schools are committed to providing a school environment that will prepare children and arm them with the skills needed to succeed, however the future.
In these times there can be no denying the fact that in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as "international communication skills."
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
