North Korea says it will not be unilaterally disarmed without gaining confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that the sanctions continued on Saturday were deepening mistrust of the United States and the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual body from around the world of the General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant measures that show goodwill" in the past year, such as banning nuclear and missile tests, dismantling areas where nuclear tests were conducted, and pledging not to add weapons and nuclear technology.
However, we are not seeing any response to this from the US," he said.
Without trust in the U.S., our national security will have no self-confidence, and under these circumstances there is no way that we unilaterally disarm ourselves first.
While Ri reiterated North Korea's usual complaints about Washington's resistance to a phased approach to the nuclear disarmament process where North Korea would be assessed due to the gradual steps it has taken, his statement seemed important because it did not exclude unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done before.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a summit held for the first time between a sitting U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward "nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula" as Trump pledged guarantees regarding North Korea's security.
North Korea has demanded an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease strict international sanctions on North Korea.
The U.S. insists on conducting "nuclear disarmament" first and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a binding manner, even by opposing the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
The perception that sanctions can put us to our knees is the dreams of people who are uninformed about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of the sanctions is deepening our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, a statement the U.S. leader made earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister underlined three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party on the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the US, the process of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have come to this situation without a way out."
Despite this, the tone used in the New Speech was deeply different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that the deployment of U.S. territory targeted by North Korean missiles was inevitable as "Mr. President Devil" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, thanked Kim for the courage shown in taking steps to disarm, but said there is still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions should continue to be active until North Korea conducts nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a timeline for that, saying, "If it takes two years, three years, or five months - it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue strongly and unequivocally until the full and final verification of nuclear disarmament is carried out."
The Security Council has unanimously decided to increase sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an effort to end Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go so well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying there had been progress, and within hours North Korea denounced him for having carried out "mafia-style demands."
North Korea pledged at a meeting with Moon this month to disarm a missile zone and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "appropriate measures."
He said Kim had told him the "relevant measures" he was seeking were security guarantees that Trump pledged in Singapore and moving toward normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take lessons on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has included all students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of study machoes through the use of caffeine by these 'sleepers'.
An academic observed that the world's number one university students often don't know when it comes to the most basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start this course after giving a reference to the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
At the end of it, a girl approached me and said, 'Why is this being said to me now, in my last year?'
She said no one had ever spoken to her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the essential elements of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of medical services at the university, said the university decided to introduce this course after finding out that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a variety of interactive tasks.
On one side is a view of a dorm room, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain the effects of caffeine and lighting and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the hours to be spent in bed.
In another part, participants were explained how sleep deprivation in the long term increases the risks of heart attack, ischemic, depression, and cancer.
A map of the camp, with iconic icons, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - as you have the right to know, the health impact when choosing to smoke," Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in spending a 'sleepless night' continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was an ever-increasing problem.
Making sure you get enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student's 'secret weapon' to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation leads the brain to a mode of hunger, making them feel constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to turn it into a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all students of graduate studies to complete a similar study program before joining competing institutions.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students should set an hour's bell on when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of blue light coming out of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can lead to problems falling asleep.
