National Trust observes the secret life of bats
A new research being conducted by a company in Scotland's mountainous areas aims to find out how bats use the ground to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the new findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and will help defensive activities in the future.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow ordinary night bats and those called soprano pipistrelles as well as brown-ears and Daubenton bats in Inverewe gardens, in West Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key points throughout the area to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field studies using hand detectors.
The sound analysis to be carried out by experts for all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and what each species does.
Then, a report and a map of their habitat will be drawn up to give a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature protection adviser for NTS, hopes the findings will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information would help determine the benefits of settlement administration, such as the creation of pastures and how to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The number of bats in Scotland and across the UK has declined significantly over the past century.
They are under the threat of construction and development works that have an impact on nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as do adhesive paper or chemical components of building materials, as well as domestic animal attacks.
In fact, the bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching the prey.
They use a sophisticated location-finding technique through sounds to accurately determine insects and obstacles during flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land in the country, takes the bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct studies, nest inspections and sometimes engage in rescue programs.
The organization has even raised the first and only reserve in Scotland dedicated to bats in Threave, Dumfries and Galloway, which serves as home to eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland.
The administrator of this reserve, David Thompson, says that this country is the ideal territory for them.
Here in Threave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many ancient trees and all the right habitat.
But there are still a lot of things about bats that remain unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand more about what they need to develop."
He emphasizes the importance of carrying out the screenings for bats before carrying out the property maintenance works because there is a possibility that the unintentional destruction of a nest can kill up to 400 female and young bats, thus wiping out the entire population of an area.
Night nudes are protected and killing, harassing and disturbing them or destroying their nests is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish clerk at the Nightkeeping Trust, encourages people to become part of the help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species, we just don't know how their population is moving."
